revision.text:
{{Infobox event | title = Valletta gunpowder factory explosion | image = Malta - Valletta - Triq il-Merkanti 07 ies.jpg | caption = The [[Church of the Jesuits, Valletta|Jesuit church]], which was severely damaged in the explosion | time = | date = 12 September 1634 | location = [[Valletta]], [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|Malta]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|53|56|N|14|30|57|E|display=inline,title}} | type = Gunpowder factory explosion | cause = | reported deaths = 22 | reported injuries = Unknown | reported property damage = Significant }}
On 12 September 1634, a [[Knights Hospitaller|Hospitaller]] gunpowder factory in [[Valletta]], [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|Malta]] accidentally blew up, killing 22 people and causing severe damage to a number of buildings. The factory had been built sometime in the late 16th or early 17th centuries, replacing an earlier one in [[Fort St. Angelo]] in [[Birgu]]. It was located in the lower part of Valletta, close to the [[Slaves' Prison]].<ref name="spiteri"/>
The explosion damaged the nearby [[Church of the Jesuits, Valletta|Jesuit church]] and [[Old University Building, Valletta|college]].<ref name="spiteri"/> The church's façade was rebuilt in around 1647 by the architect Francesco Buonamici, while the damaged parts of the college were also rebuilt after the explosion.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the University of Malta Valletta Campus|url=https://www.um.edu.mt/conferenceunit/venue/historicalinformation|website=[[University of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615131223/https://www.um.edu.mt/conferenceunit/venue/historicalinformation|archivedate=15 June 2017|date=20 January 2015}}</ref>
The gunpowder factory was not rebuilt. In around 1667, a new factory was constructed in [[Floriana]], far away from any residential areas. This factory was incorporated into the Ospizio complex in the early 18th century.<ref name="spiteri">{{cite journal|last1=Spiteri|first1=Stephen C.|authorlink1=Stephen C. Spiteri|title=Hospitaller Gunpowder Magazines|journal=Arx – International Journal of Military Architecture and Fortification|date=2012|volume=Occasional Papers|issue=2|url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/index.php/Journals/arx-occasional-papers-hospitaller-gunpowder-magazines.html|pages=5–7}}</ref>
