[[File:Victory day Kiev 2.jpg|thumb|A color guard in Kiev.]] The '''2010 Kiev Victory Day Parade''' was held on May 9, 2010 in [[Kiev]], honoring the 65th anniversary of the [[Soviet Union]]'s victory in the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Great Patriotic War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=The Victory Parade took place in Kiev, Ukraine on May 9, 2010 to celebrate the 65th anniversary of Victory in the Great Patriotic War.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.people.cn/90001/90783/91321/6978821.html|title=Ukraine holds military parade to mark 65th anniversary Victory Day - People's Daily Online|website=en.people.cn|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref> (In 2015, the [[Ukrainian parliament]] replaced the term "[[Great Patriotic War (term)|Great Patriotic War]]" with "[[Second World War]]" as part of a set of [[Decommunization in Ukraine|decommunization laws]].<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/ukraine-purges-symbols-its-communist-past-321663 Ukraine Purges Symbols of Its Communist Past], [[Newsweek]], (10 April 2015)</ref>) Military vehicles, and soldiers in Soviet Army uniforms, marched on [[Khreschatyk Street]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.kievukraine.info/2010/05/ukraine-marks-victory-day-with-military.html?m=1|title=Ukraine Marks Victory Day With Military Parade|website=news.kievukraine.info|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref> Inspecting the parade was the [[Chief of the General Staff]] of the Armed Forces [[General of the Army]] [[Ivan Svyda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=Inspecting the parade was the Chief of General Staff of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, Ivan Svyda.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The commander of the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]], Colonel General [https://ru.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Воробьёв,_Геннадий_Петрович Gennady Vorobyov], Commandedg the Parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=Commanding the parade was the commander of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, Colonel-General Gennady Vorobyov.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[President of Ukraine|President]] of [[Ukraine]] [[Viktor Yanukovych]] delivered a jubilee address.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=Delivering the address was the President of Ukraine, Commander-in-Chief of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, Viktor Yanukovych.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> 2,500 members of the Ukrainian Armed Forces troops from [[Russia]] and [[Belarus]] took part in the parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=More than 2,500 thousand members of the Ukrainian Armed Forces and other military units took part in the parade. Troops from Russia and Belarus also took part in the parade.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/multimedia/photo/a-grand-parade-befitting-a-grand-victory-65-years-200686|title=A grand parade befitting a grand victory 65 years ago - May. 13, 2010|work=KyivPost|access-date=2017-10-19|language=en-US}}</ref> 17 military orchestras took part in the parade under the command of the Chief of the [[Military Music Department of the General Staff of the Ukrainian Armed Forces]], Major General [[Volodymyr Derkach]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joHF8F2Ki3M&list=PL030PgM6el9LS5a8XmpWCMLCjSPtrusC_&index=20|title=Musical accompaniment by 17 military orchestras under the guidance of the Chief of the Military Music Department of the General Staff of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, People's Artist of Ukraine, Major General Volodymyr Derkach.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
