{{merge to|2021 Asian Youth Games|discuss=Talk:2021 Asian Youth Games#Merger proposal|date=September 2018}} The '''2017 Asian Youth Games''' were to be an international [[multi-sport event]]. Initially planned to be hosted by the city of [[Hambantota]], [[Sri Lanka]], a new host for the 2017 AYG were to be decided at a future [[Olympic Council of Asia]] general assembly after Sri Lanka lost its hosting rights.<ref name="a">{{cite news|title=Asian Youth Games: Sri Lanka loses right to be host, OCA to offer Indonesia the chance|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/sport/more-sport-stories/story/asian-youth-games-sri-lanka-loses-right-be-host-oca-offer-indone|accessdate=22 May 2015|publisher=The Strait Times|date=22 May 2015}}</ref> It has now been decided to postpone until [[2021 Asian Youth Games|2021]] in [[Surabaya]], [[Indonesia]].<ref name=postponement>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1041977/exclusive-asian-youth-games-set-to-be-postponed-until-2021-after-jakarta-withdraw|title=Exclusive: Asian Youth Games set to be postponed until 2021 after Jakarta withdraw|publisher=Inside the Games|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>
== Bidding == Hambantota decided on bidding for the games after losing the vote to stage the [[2018 Commonwealth Games]] which were eventually awarded to the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/34-7964-news-detail-failed-hambantota-now-settles-for-youth-asian-games.html |title=Failed Hambantota now settles for Youth Asian Games |author=Champika Fernando |date=15 June 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> On 15 June 2012 the president of the [[Olympic Council of Asia]] [[Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah]] announced that [[Hambantota]] had been chosen as the host of the games. [[Indonesia]], [[Qatar]], [[Thailand]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Uzbekistan]] also bid to stage the games but were ultimately unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.srilankaolympic.org/2012/06/sri-lanka-to-host-2017-asian-youth-games/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130415203504/http://www.srilankaolympic.org/2012/06/sri-lanka-to-host-2017-asian-youth-games/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=15 April 2013 |title=Sri Lanka to host 2017 Asian Youth Games |date=15 June 2012 |publisher=[[National Olympic Committee of Sri Lanka]] |accessdate=8 November 2012 }}</ref>
Sri Lanka was stripped of its hosting rights by OCA due to political interference of its government with its national Olympic committee. Indonesia was offered by OCA to take over as hosts and the games were suggested test event for the [[2018 Asian Games]]. Sri Lanka's replacement was set to be decided at an OCA general assembly scheduled in September 2015,<ref name="a"/> but it has now been decided to postpone the event for 4 years as no replacement host city was found.<ref name=postponement/>
