{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox magazine | title = Abyad wa Aswad | image_file = | image_size = | image_caption = | editor = | editor_title = | frequency = [[Weekly]] | circulation = | category = [[Political journalism|Political magazine]] | company = | publisher = | founded =2001 | firstdate = {{start date and age|2002|7|22|df=yes}} | country = [[Syria]] | based = [[Damascus]] | language = [[Arabic language|Arabic]] | website = | issn = }}
'''''Abyad wa Aswad''''' ("Black and White" in English) is an [[Arabic]] independent weekly [[Political journalism|political]] [[Culture Magazine|culture magazine]] published in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]. The magazine is privately owned.
==Profile== ''Abyad wa Aswad'' was established in early 2001.<ref name=salam>{{cite web|author=Salam Kawakibi|title=The Private Media in Syria|url=http://acimedit.be/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/The-private-media-in-Syria.pdf|work=University of Amsterdam and Hivos|accessdate=16 September 2014|year=2010}}</ref> Publication license was granted in 2002, being the first independent political weekly in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Attacks on the Press 2002: Syria|url=http://cpj.org/2003/03/attacks-on-the-press-2002-syria.php|work=CPJ|accessdate=2 October 2013|date=31 March 2003}}</ref> The first issue appeared on 22 July 2002.<ref name=ap2>{{cite news|title=Syria's 1st Private Magazine Arrives|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/2002/Syria-s-1st-Private-Magazine-Arrives/id-230da209940c86281857291e240276fa|accessdate=2 October 2013|work=Associated Press|date=22 July 2002}}</ref> The magazine, headquartered in Damascus, is a privately owned publication.<ref>{{cite web|title=Syrian media|url=http://fpwatch.com/?p=85|work=Foreign Policy Watch|accessdate=2 October 2013|author=Sami Moubayed|date=17 April 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215213/http://fpwatch.com/?p=85|archive-date=4 October 2013|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=arnews3>{{cite news|title=Two private Syrian publications criticize the information and foreign ministries |url=http://www.arabicnews.com/ansub/Daily/Day/030714/2003071402.html |accessdate=2 October 2013 |work=Arabic News |date=14 July 2003 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213618/http://www.arabicnews.com/ansub/Daily/Day/030714/2003071402.html |archivedate=4 October 2013 }}</ref> Bilal Turkmani, former defense minister [[Hasan Turkmani]]'s son, is the owner of ''Abyad wa Aswad''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Blandford|first=Nicholas|title=Syrian media liberalisation causes a stir|journal=The Middle East|date=1 February 2005|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Syrian+media+liberalisation+causes+a+stir%3A+Nicholas+Blanford+reports...-a0128792708|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ninth: The press, mass media, journalistic and mass media freedoms|url=http://www.shrc.org/en/?p=20064|work=Syrian Human Rights Committee|accessdate=2 October 2013|date=26 June 2004}}</ref>
The magazine adopts a critical attitude towards the activities of the [[Syrian government]]<ref name=salam/> and contains reform-oriented articles.<ref name=nb4>{{cite news|title=Censors ease up on Syrian press|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/1228/p06s01-wome.html|accessdate=2 October 2013|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=28 December 2004|author=Nicholas Blandford|location=Damascus}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Syria Country Report |url=http://www.bti-project.org/countryreports/mena/syr/2010/index.nc |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131002181955/http://www.bti-project.org/countryreports/mena/syr/2010/index.nc |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2 October 2013 |work=BTI |accessdate=2 October 2013 |year=2010 }}</ref> For instance, the magazine criticized the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Syria)|Syrian foreign ministry]] in 2003 for not attending the special session of the [[UN Security Council]] during which UN Security Council resolution 1483 that was about ending the [[sanctions against Iraq]] had been voted.<ref name=arnews3/> It further argued that both the foreign ministry and other governmental bodies had no dynamism and flexibility.<ref name=arnews3/>
