{{notability|date=July 2011}} '''''Computational and Systems Neuroscience''''' (COSYNE or CoSyNe) is an annual [[scientific conference]] for the exchange of experimental and theoretical/computational approaches to problems in [[systems neuroscience]]. It is an important meeting for [[computational neuroscience|computational neuroscientists]] where many levels of approaches are discussed.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Marr|first1=David|title=Vision|date=2010|publisher=MIT press|isbn=9780262290371|page=365|url=https://doi.org/10.7551/mitpress/9780262514620.001.0001}}</ref> It is a single track-meeting with oral and [[poster session]]s and attracts about 800-900 participants from a variety of disciplines, including neuroscience, computer science and machine learning. Until 2018, the 3-day long main meeting was held in [[Salt Lake City]], followed by two days of workshops at [[Snowbird, Utah]]. In 2018, COSYNE moved to Denver (3 days) and Breckenridge (2 days).
== History == COSYNE grew out of the Neural Information and Coding (NIC) meetings founded by Anthony Zador in 1996.<ref name="NIC">{{cite web|last1=Zador|first1=Tony|title=Neural Information and Coding workshops|url=http://zadorlab.cshl.edu/NIC.html|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Park|first1=Il Memming|title=Alex Pouget (#theoryMatters interview #04)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wZphn2IocwU&t=5m2s|accessdate=26 December 2016|website=youtube.com}}</ref> The first COSYNE was organized in 2004 by Michael Shadlen, Alexander Pouget, [[Carlos Brody]] and [[Anthony Zador]].<ref name="COSYNEweb">{{cite web|url=http://cosyne.org/|title=Computational and Systems Neuroscience|website=COSYNE.ORG|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> The current Executive Committee consists of Alexander Pouget, [[Zachary Mainen]], Stephanie Palmer and Anthony Zador.
