{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox park | name = Hyde Park | photo = Aerial view of Hyde Park.jpg | photo_width = 300 | photo_caption = Hyde Park (in foreground) and [[Kensington Gardens]] | type = Public park | location = [[London]], England | map = United Kingdom London Westminster | map_width = 300 | map_alt = | map_caption = Location within central London | coords = {{coord|51.508611|N|0.163611|W|region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | area = {{convert|350|acre|ha}} | created = {{Start_date|df=yes|1637}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/history.cfm |title=Hyde Park History |publisher=Royalparks.org.uk |date=15 December 2003 |accessdate=11 December 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060113171536/http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/history.cfm |archivedate=13 January 2006 |df= }}</ref> | operator = [[The Royal Parks]] | visitation_num = | status = Open year round | website = {{URL|https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park}} }}
'''Hyde Park''' is a [[Listed building#Heritage protection|Grade I-listed]] major park in [[Central London]]. It is the largest of four [[Royal Parks of London|Royal Parks]] that form a chain from the entrance of [[Kensington Palace]] through [[Kensington Gardens]] and Hyde Park, via Hyde Park Corner and [[Green Park]] past the main entrance to [[Buckingham Palace]]. The park is divided by the [[Serpentine (lake)|Serpentine]] and [[the Long Water]] lakes.
The park was established by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] in 1536 when he took the land from [[Westminster Abbey]] and used it as a hunting ground. It opened to the public in 1637 and quickly became popular, particularly for [[May Day]] parades. Major improvements occurred in the early 18th century under the direction of [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]]. Several [[duel]]s took place in Hyde Park during this time, often involving members of the nobility. [[The Great Exhibition]] of 1851 was held in the park, for which [[The Crystal Palace]], designed by [[Joseph Paxton]], was erected.
[[Free speech]] and [[demonstration (protest)|demonstrations]] have been a key feature of Hyde Park since the 19th century. [[Speaker's Corner]] has been established as a point of free speech and debate since 1872, while the [[Chartists]], the [[Reform League]], the [[suffragettes]], and the [[15 February 2003 anti-war protest|Stop the War Coalition]] have all held protests there. In the late 20th century, the park became known for holding large-scale free [[rock music]] concerts, featuring groups such as [[Pink Floyd]], [[The Rolling Stones]] and [[Queen (band)|Queen]]. Commercial concerts have continued into the 21st century, such as [[Live 8]] in 2005.
==Geography== Hyde Park is the largest [[Royal Parks of London|Royal Park]] in London. It is bounded on the north by [[Bayswater Road]], to the east by [[Park Lane]], and to the south by [[Knightsbridge]]. Further north is [[Paddington]], further east is [[Mayfair]] and further south is [[Belgravia]].{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=423}} To the southeast, outside the park, is [[Hyde Park Corner]], beyond which is [[Green Park, London|Green Park]], [[St. James's Park]] and [[Buckingham Palace Gardens]].<ref name=a-z/> The park has been Grade I listed on the [[Register of Historic Parks and Gardens of special historic interest in England|Register of Historic Parks and Gardens]] since 1987.<ref name=NHLEGarden>{{NHLE|num=100814|desc=Hyde Park|access-date=11 July 2017|mode=cs2}}</ref>
To the west, Hyde Park merges with [[Kensington Gardens]]. The dividing line runs approximately between Alexandra Gate to Victoria Gate via West Carriage Drive and the Serpentine Bridge. The [[Serpentine (lake)|Serpentine]] is to the south of the park area.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=423}} Kensington Gardens has been separate from Hyde Park since 1728, when [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]] divided them. Hyde Park covers 142 hectares (350 acres),<ref name=royalparks>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/|title=Hyde Park|publisher=Royalparks.org.uk|date=|accessdate=11 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925180809/http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/|archivedate=25 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Kensington Gardens covers 111 hectares (275 acres),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/kensington_gardens/ |title=Kensington Gardens |publisher=Royalparks.org.uk |date= |accessdate=11 December 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yo0tndiN?url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/kensington_gardens/ |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> giving a total area of 253 hectares (625 acres).{{efn|By comparison, the combined area of Hyde Park and Kensington Gardens is larger than the [[Monaco|Principality of Monaco]] ({{convert|196|ha|acre|disp=or|abbr=off}}), though smaller than the [[Bois de Boulogne]] in Paris (845 hectares, or 2090 acres), New York City's [[Central Park]] ({{convert|341|ha|acre|disp=or|abbr=off}}), and Dublin's [[Phoenix Park]] (707 hectares, or 1,750 acres).}} During daylight, the two parks merge seamlessly into each other, but Kensington Gardens closes at dusk, and Hyde Park remains open throughout the year from 5 a.m. until midnight.<ref name=a-z/>
==History== ===Early history=== The park's name comes from the Manor of Hyde, which was the northeast sub-division of the manor of [[Eia]] (the other two sub-divisions were Ebury and Neyte) and appears as such in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref name=onl/> The name is believed to be of Saxon origin, and means a unit of land, the [[hide (unit)|hide]], that was appropriate for the support of a single family and dependents.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199609086.001.0001/acref-9780199609086-e-7190?rskey=krfED0&result=7271|title=Dictionary of British Place Names|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0-191-73944-6|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414000944/http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199609086.001.0001/acref-9780199609086-e-7190?rskey=krfED0&result=7271|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Through the [[Middle Ages]], it was property of [[Westminster Abbey]], and the woods in the manor were used both for firewood and shelter for [[game (hunting)|game]].<ref name=onl>{{cite book|first=Edward|last=Walford|title=Hyde Park|work=Old and New London|volume=4|location=London|year=1878|pp=375–405|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/old-new-london/vol4/pp375-405|accessdate=13 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128121110/http://www.british-history.ac.uk/old-new-london/vol4/pp375-405|archivedate=28 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
===16th–17th centuries=== Hyde Park was created for hunting by Henry Vlll in 1536 after he acquired the manor of Hyde from the Abbey.{{sfn|Self|2014|p=28}} It was enclosed as a [[Deer park (England)|deer park]] and remained a private hunting ground until [[James I of England|James I]] permitted limited access to gentlefolk,{{sfn|Humphreys|Bamber|2003|p=284}} appointing a ranger to take charge. [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] created the Ring (north of the present Serpentine boathouses), and in 1637 he opened the park to the general public.{{sfn|Porter|2000|p=279}} It quickly became a popular gathering place, particularly for [[May Day]] celebrations. At the start of the [[English Civil War]] in 1642, a series of fortifications were built along the east side of the park, including forts at what is now [[Marble Arch]], [[Mount Street, London|Mount Street]] and [[Hyde Park Corner]]. The latter included a strongpoint where visitors to London could be checked and vetted.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=423}}
In 1652, during the [[Interregnum (England)|Interregnum]], Parliament ordered the then {{convert|620|acre|adj=on}} park to be sold for "ready money". It realised £17,000 with an additional £765 6s 2d for the resident deer.<ref name=Timbs>{{cite book|first=John|last=Timbs|author-link=John Timbs|title=Curiosities of London: Exhibiting the Most Rare and Remarkable Objects of Interest in the Metropolis|url=http://libertydrives.org.uk/#page/644/mode/1u|year=1855|publisher=D. Bogue|page=644|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/#page/644/mode/1up|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/commons-jrnl/vol7/p222|title=House of Commons Journal Volume 7: 27 November 1652|work=British History Online|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> During the [[Great Plague of London]] in 1665, Hyde Park was used as a military camp.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=423}} Following the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration of the Monarchy]] in 1660, [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] retook ownership of Hyde Park and enclosed it in a brick wall. He restocked deer in what is now Buck Hill in Kensington Gardens. The May Day parade continued to be a popular event; [[Samuel Pepys]] took part in the park's celebrations in 1663 while attempting to gain the King's favour.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|pp=423–424}}
===18th century=== [[File:James Douglas, 4th Duke of Hamilton; Charles Mohun, 4th Baron Mohun from NPG.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Hamilton–Mohun Duel]] of 1712. [[Charles Mohun, 4th Baron Mohun]] fighting [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton]] in Hyde Park; both lost their lives.]] In 1689, [[William III of England|William III]] moved his residence to [[Kensington Palace]] on the far side of Hyde Park and had a drive laid out across its southern edge which was known as the King's Private Road. The drive is still in existence as a wide straight gravelled carriage track leading west from [[Hyde Park Corner]] across the southern boundary of Hyde Park towards Kensington Palace and now known as [[Rotten Row]], possibly a corruption of ''rotteran'' (to muster),<ref name=onl/> ''Ratten Row'' (roundabout way), ''Route du roi'', or ''rotten'' (the soft material with which the road is covered).<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.bartleby.com/81/14534.html |title='Dictionary of Phrase and Fable |author=E Cobham Brewer |authorlink=Ebenezer Cobham Brewer |publisher=Henry Altemus, 1898; Bartleby.com, 2000 |accessdate=29 January 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010183403/http://bartleby.com/81/14534.html |archivedate=10 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is believed to be the first road in London to be lit at night, which was done to deter [[highwayman|highwaymen]]. In 1749, [[Horace Walpole]] was robbed while travelling through the park from [[Holland House]].{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}} The row was used by the wealthy for horseback rides in the early 19th century.<ref name="world and its people">{{cite book|last = Dunton|first = Larkin|authorlink =|title = The World and its People|publisher = Silver, Burdett|series =|year = 1894|page = 30}}</ref>
Hyde Park was a popular [[duelling]] spot during the 18th century, with 172 taking place, leading to 63 fatalities.{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=49}} The [[Hamilton–Mohun Duel]] took place there in 1712 when [[Charles Mohun, 4th Baron Mohun]] fought [[James Hamilton, 4th Duke of Hamilton]]. Baron Mohun was killed instantly, while the Duke died shortly afterwards. [[John Wilkes]] fought [[Samuel Martin (Secretary to the Treasury)|Samuel Martin]] in 1772, as did [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]] with Captain Thomas Mathews over the latter's libellous comments about Sheridan's fiancee [[Elizabeth Ann Linley]]. [[Edward Thurlow, 1st Baron Thurlow]] fought Andrew Stuart in a Hyde Park duel in 1770.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}} Military executions were common in Hyde Park at this time; [[John Rocque's Map of London, 1746]] marks a point inside the park, close to the [[Tyburn gallows]], as "where soldiers are shot."{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=37}}{{efn|This location is now where the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]] [[Edgware Road]] meets the [[A40 road (Great Britain)|A40]] [[Marble Arch]].<ref>{{cite map|title=John Rocque's Map of London|year=1746|url=https://www.locatinglondon.org/|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704165426/https://www.locatinglondon.org/|archivedate=4 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}
[[File:Hyde Park London from 1833 Schmollinger map.jpg|thumb|Hyde Park c. 1833: Rotten Row is "The King's Private Road"]] The first coherent landscaping in Hyde Park began in 1726. It was undertaken by [[Charles Bridgeman]] for [[George I of the United Kingdom|King George I]], but following the king's death the following year, it continued with approval of his daughter-in-law, [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]].{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=112}} Work was undertaken under the supervision of Charles Withers, the [[Surveyor General of Woods, Forests, Parks, and Chases|Surveyor-General of Woods and Forests]]. The principal effect of the work was to sub-divide Hyde Park and create Kensington Gardens.{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=40}}{{efn|Bridgeman was Royal Gardener 1728–38; designed the [[Round Pond (London)|Round Pond]] in Kensington Gardens. Peter Willis, ''Charles Bridgeman and the English Landscape Garden'' (London and New York) 1978, devotes a chapter to Bridgeman's [[Royal Commission]]s.}} The Serpentine was formed by damming the [[River Westbourne]], which runs through the park from [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]] towards the Thames. It is divided from [[the Long Water]] by a bridge designed by [[George Rennie (engineer)|George Rennie]] in 1826.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
The work was completed in 1733. The [[Thomas Thynne, 2nd Viscount Weymouth|2nd Viscount Weymouth]] was made Ranger of Hyde Park in 1739 and shortly after began digging the Serpentine lakes at [[Longleat]].<ref>[[Timothy Mowl]], "Rococo and Later Landscaping at Longleat", ''Garden History'' '''23'''.1 (Summer 1995, pp. 56–66) p. 59, noting Jacob Larwood, ''The Story of London Parks'' 1881:41.</ref> A [[Gunpowder magazine|powder magazine]] was built north of the Serpentine in 1805.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
===19th–21st centuries=== [[File:Pissarro Hyde Park.jpg|thumb|left|''Hyde Park'', 1890, by [[Camille Pissarro]], showing the footpath along the southern bank of the Serpentine]] Hyde Park hosted a Great Fair in the summer of 1814 to celebrate the [[Allied sovereigns' visit to England]], and exhibited various stalls and shows. The [[Battle of Trafalgar]] was re-enacted on the Serpentine, with a band playing the National Anthem while the French fleet sank into the lake. The coronation of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] in 1821 was celebrated with a fair in the park, including an [[air balloon]] and firework displays.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
One of the most important events to take place in Hyde Park was the [[Great Exhibition of 1851]]. [[The Crystal Palace]] was constructed on the south side of the park.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}} The public did not want the building to remain after the closure of the exhibition, and its architect, [[Joseph Paxton]], raised funds and purchased it. He had it moved to [[Sydenham Hill]] in South London.<ref>Purbrick, Louise: ''The Great Exhibition of 1851: New Interdisciplinary Essays'': 2001: Manchester University Press, p. 122</ref> Another significant event was the first [[Victoria Cross]] investiture, on 26 June 1857, when 62 men were decorated by [[Queen Victoria]] in the presence of [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] and other members of the Royal Family, including their future son-in-law Crown Prince Frederick of Prussia, later [[Frederick III, German Emperor|Emperor Frederick III]].<ref>Crook, M. J.: ''The Evolution of the Victoria Cross'': 1975: Midas Books, pp. 49–52.</ref>
The Hyde Park Lido sits on the south bank of the Serpentine. It opened in 1930 to provide improved support for bathing and sunbathing in the park, which had been requested by the [[naturism|naturist]] group, the Sunlight League. The Lido and accompanying Pavilion was designed by the Commissioner of Works, [[George Lansbury]], and was half funded by a £5,000 (now £{{inflation|UK|5000|1930|fmt=c|r=-3}}) donation from Major Colin Cooper (1892-1938). It still sees regular use in the summer into the 21st century.{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=137}}<ref name="RPHist"/>
Hyde Park has been a major venue for several Royal jubilees and celebrations. For the [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria]] in 1887, a party was organised on 22 June where around 26,000 school children were given a free meal as a gift. The Queen and the Prince of Wales made an unexpected appearance at the event. Victoria remained fond of Hyde Park in the final years of her life and often drove there twice a day.{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=91}} As part of the [[Silver Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II|Queen's Silver Jubilee]] in 1977, a Jubilee Exhibition was set up in Hyde Park,<ref name="RPHist">{{cite web|title =Hyde Park History & Architecture|publisher =The Royal Parks|year =2007|url=http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/history.cfm|accessdate =5 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810110602/http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/history.cfm|archivedate =10 August 2007}}</ref> with the Queen and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] visiting on 30 June.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court Circular|newspaper=[[The Times]]|location=London, England|date=1 July 1977|p=20|accessdate=16 August 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS335773921&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|subscription=yes|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, a major festival took place in the park as part of the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee]] celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/press-and-media/press-releases/2012-press-releases/sainsburys-announces-jubilee-family-festival|title=Sainsbury's announces Jubilee Family Festival|publisher=Royal Parks|date=17 February 2012|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417072037/https://www.royalparks.org.uk/press-and-media/press-releases/2012-press-releases/sainsburys-announces-jubilee-family-festival|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 6 February, the [[King's Troop, Royal Horse Artillery]] fired a 41-gun Royal Salute at Hyde Park Corner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9064061/Gun-salutes-mark-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee.html|title=Gun salutes mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee|newspaper=The Daily Telegraphy|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=16 August 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502071940/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9064061/Gun-salutes-mark-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee.html|archivedate=2 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[File:Winter Wonderland 5276970971.jpg|thumb|The [[Hyde Park Winter Wonderland|Winter Wonderland]] festival has been a popular Christmas event in Hyde Park since 2007.]] On 20 July 1982, in the [[Hyde Park and Regents Park bombings]], two devices linked to the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] caused the death of eight members of the [[Household Cavalry]] and the [[Royal Green Jackets]] and seven horses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/20/newsid_2515000/2515343.stm |title=1982: IRA bombs cause carnage in London |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=25 January 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308085004/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/20/newsid_2515000/2515343.stm |archivedate=8 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A memorial was constructed to the left of the Albert Gate to commemorate the soldiers and horses killed in the blast.{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=137-138}}
Since 2007, Hyde Park has played host to the annual [[Hyde Park Winter Wonderland|Winter Wonderland]] event, which features numerous Christmas-themed markets, along with various rides and attractions, alongside bars and restaurants. It has become one of the largest Christmas events in Europe, having attracted over 14 million visitors as of 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/11/27/495328/London-Hyde-park-hosting-annual-Winter-Wonderland|title=London Hyde park hosting annual family-friendly Winter Wonderland|publisher=Press TV|accessdate=8 December 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128141404/http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/11/27/495328/London-Hyde-park-hosting-annual-Winter-Wonderland|archivedate=28 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwrevents.com/winterwonderland|title=Hyde Park Winter Wonderland|publisher=PWR Events|accessdate=8 December 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220192629/http://www.pwrevents.com/winterwonderland|archivedate=20 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has expanded to include the largest ice rink in London, live entertainment and circuses.<ref>{{cite news|first=Harriet|last=Addison|title=Get your skates on this weekend|newspaper=The Times|location=London, England|date=26 November 2011|p=3 [S1]|accessdate=16 August 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF504307988&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|subscription=yes|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
On 18 September 2010, Hyde Park was the setting for a prayer vigil with [[Pope Benedict XVI]] as part of his [[Pope Benedict XVI's visit to the United Kingdom|visit to the United Kingdom]], attended by around 80,000 people. A large crowd assembled along the Mall to see the Pope arrive for his address.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-hyde-park-speech|title=Pope tells Hyde Park crowd that 'they too suffer for their faith'|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 September 2010|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417072656/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-hyde-park-speech|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Owen|title=Not bad for a man maligned as a Teutonic hardliner|newspaper=The Times|location=London, England|date=20 September 2010|p=8|accessdate=16 August 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF504122324&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|subscription=yes|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> An attempt to assassinate the Pope had been foiled after five street cleaners were spotted within a mile of Hyde Park, and arrested along with sixth suspect.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Brown|first2=Ruth|last2=Gledhill|first3=Adam|last3=Fresco|title=Pope's rallying cry|newspaper=The Times|location=London, England|date=18 September 2010|p=1|accessdate=16 August 2017|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF504121370&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|subscription=yes|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Grand Entrance== [[File:Entrée Hyde Park.JPG|thumb|left|[[Decimus Burton]]'s Hyde Park Gate/Screen]] During the late 18th century, plans were made to replace the old toll gate at Hyde Park Corner with a grander entrance, following the gentrification of the area surrounding it. The first design was put forward by [[Robert Adam]] in 1778 as a grand archway, followed by [[John Soane]]'s 1796 proposal to build a new palace adjacent to the corner in Green Park.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=425}}
Following the construction of [[Buckingham Palace]], the improvement plans were revisited. The grand entrance to the park at Hyde Park Corner was designed by [[Decimus Burton]], and was constructed in the 1820s.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=425}} Burton laid out the paths and driveways and designed a series of lodges, the Screen/Gate at Hyde Park Corner (also known as the Grand Entrance or the Apsley Gate) in 1825{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}} and the [[Wellington Arch]], which opened in 1828.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=996}} The Screen and the Arch originally formed a single composition, designed to provide a monumental transition between Hyde Park and Green Park, although the arch was moved in 1883. It originally had a statue of the Duke of Wellington on top; it was moved to [[Aldershot]] in 1883 when the arch was re-sited.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=996}}
[[File:Wellington Arch - 01.jpg|thumb|right|[[Decimus Burton]]'s [[Wellington Arch]], Hyde Park Corner]] An early description reports: <blockquote>"It consists of a screen of handsome fluted [[Ionic column]]s, with three carriage entrance archways, two foot entrances, a lodge, etc. The extent of the whole frontage is about {{convert|107|ft|m|abbr=on}}. The central entrance has a bold projection: the entablature is supported by four columns; and the volutes of the capitals of the outside column on each side of the gateway are formed in an angular direction, so as to exhibit two complete faces to view. The two side gateways, in their elevations, present two insulated Ionic columns, flanked by antae. All these entrances are finished by a blocking, the sides of the central one being decorated with a beautiful frieze, representing a naval and military triumphal procession. This frieze was designed by Mr. Henning, junior, the son of [[John Henning (1771–1851)|Mr. Henning]] who was well known for his models of the [[Elgin Marbles]]. The gates were manufactured by [[Joseph Bramah|Messrs. Bramah]]. They are of iron, bronzed, and fixed or hung to the piers by rings of gun-metal. The design consists of a beautiful arrangement of the [[Anthemion|Greek honeysuckle ornament]]; the parts being well defined, and the raffles of the leaves brought out in a most extraordinary manner."<ref>{{cite news | first=Christopher | last=Davy | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rNZQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA67 | title=New Grand Entrance into Hyde Park | work=Mechanics' Magazine and Journal of Science, Arts, and Manufactures | volume=8 | issue=65–68 | date=18 August 1827 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610125945/https://books.google.com/books?id=rNZQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA67 | archivedate=10 June 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>
The Wellington Arch was extensively restored by [[English Heritage]] between 1999–2001. It is now open to the public, who can see a view of the parks from its platforms above the porticoes.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=996}}
==Features== [[File:7 7 Hyde Park 090712.jpg|thumb|The [[7 July Memorial]] to the victims of the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]]]] Popular areas within Hyde Park include [[Speakers' Corner]] (located in the northeast corner near [[Marble Arch]]), close to the former site of the [[Tyburn, London|Tyburn gallows]],{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=860}} and [[Rotten Row]], which is the northern boundary of the site of [[the Crystal Palace]].<ref name=a-z/>
===Botany=== Flowers were first planted in Hyde Park in 1860 by [[William Andrews Nesfield]]. The next year, the Italian Water Garden was constructed at Victoria Gate, including fountains and a [[summer house]]. Queen Anne's Alcove was designed by [[Christopher Wren|Sir Christopher Wren]] and was moved to the park from its original location in Kensington Gardens.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
During the late 20th century, over 9,000 [[elm tree]]s in Hyde Park were killed by [[Dutch elm disease]]. This included many trees along the great avenues planted by Queen Caroline, which were ultimately replaced by limes and maples.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=425}}{{sfn|Rabbitts|2015|p=113}} The park now holds {{convert|4|acre|ha}} of [[greenhouse]]s which hold the bedding plants for the Royal Parks. A scheme is available to adopt trees in the park, which helps fund their upkeep and maintenance.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=425}} A botanical curiosity is the [[weeping beech]], which is known as "the upside-down tree".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/press-and-media/factsheets-on-the-royal-parks/trees|title=Trees|publisher=Royal Parks|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412093939/https://www.royalparks.org.uk/press-and-media/factsheets-on-the-royal-parks/trees|archivedate=12 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[rose garden]], designed by Colvin & Moggridge Landscape Architects, was added in 1994.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gardenvisit.com/landscape/london/lguide/hyde-park-landscape.htm |title=Hyde Park |publisher=GardenVisit.com |date= |accessdate=11 December 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018050736/http://gardenvisit.com/landscape/london/lguide/hyde-park-landscape.htm |archivedate=18 October 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
===Statues and sculptures=== {{see also|List of public art in Hyde Park, London}} [[File:Rima, the Hudson memorial.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jacob Epstein]]'s ''Rima'' sculpture in Hyde Park]] There are a number of assorted statues and memorials around Hyde Park. The Cavalry Memorial was built in 1924 at Stanhope Gate. It moved to the Serpentine Road when Park Lane was widened to traffic in 1961.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=540}} South of the Serpentine is the [[Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Fountain|Diana, Princess of Wales memorial]], an oval stone ring fountain opened on 6 July 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4508889.stm |title=Timeline: Diana memorial fountain |work=BBC News |date=2 November 2005 |accessdate=3 September 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128030132/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4508889.stm |archivedate=28 November 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> To the east of the Serpentine, just beyond the dam, is London's [[Hyde Park Holocaust memorial|Holocaust Memorial]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/1983/06/28/archive/garden-in-londons-hyde-park-is-britains-holocaust-memorial|title=Garden in London's Hyde Park is Britain's Holocaust Memorial|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=28 June 1983|accessdate=16 July 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726071937/http://www.jta.org/1983/06/28/archive/garden-in-londons-hyde-park-is-britains-holocaust-memorial|archivedate=26 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[7 July Memorial]] in the park commemorates the victims of [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/memorials,-fountains-and-statues/7-july-memorial |title=7 July Memorial |publisher=The Royal Parks |accessdate=23 January 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123211431/https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/memorials%2C-fountains-and-statues/7-july-memorial |archivedate=23 January 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
The Standing Stone is a {{convert|7|tonne|adj=on}} [[monolith]] at the centre of the Dell, to the east of Hyde Park. Made of Cornish stone, it was originally part of a drinking fountain, though an [[urban legend]] was established, claiming it was brought from [[Stonehenge]] by Charles I.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=425}}
An assortment of unusual sculptures are scattered around the park, including: ''[[Still Water (sculpture)|Still Water]]'', a massive [[horse]] head lapping up water; ''Jelly Baby Family'', a family of giant [[Jelly Babies]] standing on top of a large black cube; and ''Vroom Vroom'', which resembles a giant human hand pushing a toy car along the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lorenzoquinn.com/en/portfolio/vroom-vroom-en-3|title=Search – Lorenzo Quinn|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926213949/http://www.lorenzoquinn.com/en/portfolio/vroom-vroom-en-3|archivedate=26 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The sculptor [[Jacob Epstein]] constructed several works in Hyde Park. His memorial to the author [[William Henry Hudson]], featuring his character ''Rima'' caused public outrage when it was unveiled in 1925.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
There has been a fountain at Grosvenor Gate since 1863, designed by [[Alexander Munro (sculptor)|Alexander Munro]]. There is another fountain opposite Mount Street on the park's eastern edge.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=424}}
==Debates== [[File:Speaker's Corner Speaker.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A Protestant Christian protesting at Speakers' Corner in 2010]] Hyde Park's Speakers' Corner has acquired an international reputation for [[demonstration (protest)|demonstrations]] and other protests{{sfn|German|Rees|2012|p=294}} due to its tolerance of [[free speech]].{{sfn|Cheetham|Winkler|2011|p=371}} In 1855, a protest at the park was organised to demonstrate against [[Robert Grosvenor, 1st Baron Ebury|Robert Grosvenor]]'s attempt to ban [[Sunday trading]], including a restriction on pub opening times. [[Karl Marx]] observed approximately 200,000 protesters attended the demonstration, which involved jeering and taunting at upper-class horse carriages. A further protest occurred a week later, but this time the police attacked the crowd.{{sfn|German|Rees|2012|pp=115–116}}
In 1867 the policing of the park was entrusted to the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]], the only royal park so managed, due to the potential for trouble at Speakers' Corner. A Metropolitan Police station ('AH') is situated in the middle of the park. The 1872 Parks Regulation Act created positions of "park keeper" and also provided that "Every police constable belonging to the police force of the district in which any park, garden, or possession to which this Act applies is situate shall have the powers, privileges, and immunities of a park-keeper within such park, garden, or possession."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1872/15/pdfs/ukpga_18720015_en.pdf|title=An Act for the regulation of the Royal Parks and Gardens, 1872|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627044055/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1872/15/pdfs/ukpga_18720015_en.pdf|archivedate=27 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[File:'FREE HUGS', Speaker's Corner, Hyde Park, London.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|The [[Free Hugs Campaign]] has taken place several times at Speaker's Corner.]] Speaker's Corner became increasingly popular in the late 19th century. Visitors brought along placards, stepladders and soap boxes in order to stand out from others, while [[Heckler|heckling]] of speakers was popular. [[Donald Soper, Baron Soper]] was a regular visitor throughout the 20th century, until just before his death in 1998. The rise of the Internet, particularly [[blog]]s, has diminished the importance of Speaker's Corner as a political platform, and it is increasingly seen as simply a tourist attraction.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=860}}
As well as Speaker's Corner, several important mass demonstrations have occurred in Hyde Park. On 26 July 1886, the [[Reform League]] staged a march from their headquarters towards the park, campaigning for increased [[suffrage]] and representation. Though the police had closed the park, the crowd managed to break down the perimeter railings and get inside, leading to the event being dubbed "The Hyde Park Railings Affair". After the protests turned violent, three squadrons of [[Royal Horse Guards|Horse Guards]] and numerous Foot Guards were sent out from Marble Arch to combat the situation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/from-the-archive-blog/2011/may/12/guardian190-hyde-park-riots|title=26 July 1866: The Hyde Park Railings Affair|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 May 2011|accessdate=17 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418081456/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/from-the-archive-blog/2011/may/12/guardian190-hyde-park-riots|archivedate=18 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 21 June 1908, as part of "[[Women's Sunday]]", a reported 750,000 people marched from the [[Thames Embankment|Embankment]] to Hyde Park protesting for [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|votes for women]]. The first protest against the planned [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] took place in Hyde Park on 28 September 2002, with 150,000–350,000 in attendance.<ref name=vevers/> A further series of demonstrations happened around the world, culminating in the [[15 February 2003, anti-war protests]], part of a global demonstration against the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=nineham>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterfire.org/articles/analysis/17835-ten-demonstrations-that-changed-the-world|title=Ten demonstrations that changed the world|first=Chris|last=Nineham|work=CounterFire|date=27 May 2015|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615041043/http://www.counterfire.org/articles/analysis/17835-ten-demonstrations-that-changed-the-world|archivedate=15 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Over a million protesters are reported to have attended the Hyde Park event alone.<ref name=vevers>{{cite news|url=https://stv.tv/news/politics/1359710-not-in-our-name-marches-and-protests-against-the-iraq-war/|title=Not in our name : Marches and protests against the Iraq War|first=Dan|last=Vevers|work=STV|date=6 July 2016|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417072729/https://stv.tv/news/politics/1359710-not-in-our-name-marches-and-protests-against-the-iraq-war/|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Concerts== {{see also|List of concerts in Hyde Park}} The bandstand in Hyde Park was originally built in Kensington Gardens in 1869, moving to its current location in 1886. It became a popular place for concerts in the 1890s, featuring up to three every week. Military and brass bands continued to play into the 20th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/memorials,-fountains-and-statues/the-bandstand-in-hyde-park|title=The bandstand in Hyde Park|publisher=Royal Parks|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312153125/https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/memorials%2C-fountains-and-statues/the-bandstand-in-hyde-park|archivedate=12 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[File:Pink floyd live 8 london.jpg|thumb|250px|left|[[Pink Floyd]] performing at [[Live 8]] in Hyde Park, 2 July 2005, their last of several gigs at the park over their career]] The music management company [[Blackhill Enterprises]] held the first rock concert in Hyde Park on 29 June 1968, attended by 15,000 people. On the bill were [[Pink Floyd]], [[Roy Harper (singer)|Roy Harper]] and [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]], while [[John Peel]] later said it was "the nicest concert I’ve ever been to". Subsequently, Hyde Park has featured some of the most significant concerts in rock. The supergroup [[Blind Faith]] (featuring [[Eric Clapton]] and [[Steve Winwood]]) played their debut gig in Hyde Park on 7 June 1969. [[The Rolling Stones]] headlined a concert (later released as [[The Stones in the Park]]) on 5 July that year, two days after the death of founding member [[Brian Jones]], and is now remembered as one of the most famous gigs of the 1960s. Pink Floyd returned to Hyde Park on 18 July 1970, playing new material from ''[[Atom Heart Mother]]''. All of the early gigs from 1968–71 were free events, contrasting sharply with the later commercial endeavours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musicheritageuk.org/about-us/stones-in-the-park/further-thoughts.html|title=The Hyde Park free concerts (1968–1971)|publisher=Music Heritage|accessdate=15 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416125642/http://musicheritageuk.org/about-us/stones-in-the-park/further-thoughts.html|archivedate=16 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[Queen (band)|Queen]] played a free concert organised by [[Richard Branson]] in the park on 18 September 1976, partway through recording the album ''[[A Day at the Races (album)|A Day at the Races]]''. The band drew an audience of 150,000 – 200,000, which remains the largest crowd for a Hyde Park concert. The group were not allowed to play an encore, and police threatened to arrest frontman [[Freddie Mercury]] if he attempted to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/stadium-rock/queen-play-hyde-park/|title=Queen Play Hyde Park|work=BBC Music|accessdate=15 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918005419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/stadium-rock/queen-play-hyde-park/|archivedate=18 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
The British [[Live 8]] concert took place in Hyde Park on 2 July 2005, as a concert organised by [[Bob Geldof]] and [[Midge Ure]] to raise awareness of increased debts and poverty in the [[third world]]. Acts included [[U2]], [[Coldplay]], [[Elton John]], [[R.E.M.]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[The Who]] and [[Paul McCartney]], and the most anticipated set was the reformation of the classic 1970s line-up of Pink Floyd (including [[David Gilmour]] and [[Roger Waters]]) for the first time since 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/pink-floyd-live-8-reunion/|title=The story of Pink Floyd's Reunion at Live 8|first=Nick|last=DeRiso|publisher=Ultimate Classic Rock|date=2 July 2015|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420125002/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/pink-floyd-live-8-reunion/|archivedate=20 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The gig was the Floyd's final live performance.<ref>{{cite book|title=Echoes : The Complete Story of Pink Floyd|first=Glenn|last=Povey|p=287|publisher=3C / Mind Head Publishing|year=2007|isbn=978-0-9554624-1-2}}</ref>
Acts from each of the four nations in the UK played a gig in the park as part of the opening ceremony for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]]. The headliners were [[Duran Duran]], representing England, alongside the [[Stereophonics]] for Wales, [[Paolo Nutini]] for Scotland and [[Snow Patrol]] for Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-17904757|title=London 2012: Stereophonics play Hyde Park Olympic gig|work=BBC News|date=1 May 2012|accessdate=18 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528032535/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-17904757|archivedate=28 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2011, [[Radio 2 Live in Hyde Park]] has taken place each September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ticketmaster.co.uk/music/bbc-radio-2-live-hyde-park-confirms-huge-names-33369|title=BBC Radio 2 Live In Hyde Park confirms some huge names|publisher=Ticketmaster|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>
Local residents have become critical of Hyde Park as a concert venue, due to the sound levels, and have campaigned for a maximum sound level of 73 [[decibels]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17079203|title=Westminster Council cuts Hyde Park concert numbers|work=BBC News|date=17 February 2012|accessdate=10 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926000835/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17079203|archivedate=26 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2012, [[Bruce Springsteen]] and [[Paul McCartney]] found their microphones switched off after Springsteen had played a three-hour set during the Park's Hard Rock Calling festival, and overshot the 10:30pm curfew time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/springsteen-and-mccartney-cut-off-because-of-sound-curfew-7945142.html|title=Springsteen and McCartney cut off because of sound curfew|first=Lisa|last=Williams|work=The Independent|date=15 July 2012|accessdate=10 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714133838/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/springsteen-and-mccartney-cut-off-because-of-sound-curfew-7945142.html|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Sports== Hyde Park contains several sporting facilities, including several [[Association football pitch|football pitch]]es and a [[Tennis]] centre. There are numerous cycle paths, and horse riding is popular.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/sports-and-leisure|title=Hyde Park : Sports and leisure|publisher=Royal Parks|accessdate=18 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219195949/https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde-park/things-to-see-and-do/sports-and-leisure|archivedate=19 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
In 1998 British artist [[Marion Coutts]] recreated Hyde Park, along with [[Battersea Park|Battersea]] and [[Regent's Park]], as a set of asymmetrical [[ping-pong]] tables for her interactive installation ''Fresh Air''.<ref name="Arnaud, 2001">{{cite web|last1=Arnaud|first1=Danielle|title=Fair Play|url=http://www.daniellearnaud.com/DA2005/exhibition-fair_play.htm|website=Danielle Arnaud|accessdate=7 December 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510174446/http://www.daniellearnaud.com/DA2005/exhibition-fair_play.htm|archivedate=10 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
For the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], the park hosted the [[Triathlon at the 2012 Summer Olympics|triathlon]], which brothers [[Alistair Brownlee]] and [[Jonathan Brownlee]] took the Gold and Bronze medals<ref>{{cite news|title=The best of London 2012: Alistair Brownlee on his triathlon gold medal performance|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9467264/The-best-of-London-2012-Alistair-Brownlee-on-his-triathlon-gold-medal-performance.html|newspaper=Telegraph|date=14 August 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919091640/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9467264/The-best-of-London-2012-Alistair-Brownlee-on-his-triathlon-gold-medal-performance.html|archivedate=19 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> for [[Team GB]], and the 10&nbsp;km [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics|open water swimming]] events.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/19173435|title=Alistair and Jonny Brownlee dominate London 2012 triathlon|work=BBC Sport|date=7 August 2012|accessdate=18 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818202646/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/19173435|archivedate=18 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The park has also hosted the ITU World Triathlon Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://london.triathlon.org/|title=ITU World Triathlon London 2015|publisher=International Triathlon Union|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821062333/http://london.triathlon.org/|archivedate=21 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Transport== [[File:Hyde Park Corner stn southwest entrance.JPG|thumb|220px|Entrance to [[Hyde Park Corner tube station]], with the Grand Entrance to the left]] There are five [[London Underground]] stations located on or near the edges of Hyde Park and [[Kensington Gardens]] (which is contiguous with Hyde Park). In clockwise order starting from the south-east, they are:<ref name=tubemap>{{cite web|url=http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|title=Tube map|publisher=Transport for London|accessdate=16 April 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625083557/http://content.tfl.gov.uk/standard-tube-map.pdf|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> *[[Hyde Park Corner tube station|Hyde Park Corner]] ([[Piccadilly line]]) *[[Knightsbridge tube station|Knightsbridge]] (Piccadilly line) *[[Queensway tube station|Queensway]] ([[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]]) *[[Lancaster Gate tube station|Lancaster Gate]] (Central line) *[[Marble Arch tube station|Marble Arch]] (Central line)
[[Bayswater tube station]], on the Circle and [[District line|District]] lines, is also close to Queensway station and the north-west corner of the park. [[High Street Kensington tube station]], on the Circle and [[District line|District]] is very close to Kensington Palace located on the Southwest corner of Kensington Gardens. Paddington station, served by Bakerloo, Circle and District, and Hammersmith & City lines, is close to Lancaster Gate station and a short walk away from Hyde Park.<ref name=tubemap/>
Several main roads run around the perimeter of Hyde Park. Park Lane is part of the [[London Inner Ring Road]] and the [[London Congestion Charge]] zone boundary. The [[A4 road (England)|A4]], a major road through West London, runs along the southeastern edge of the park, while the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]], a major road to [[Milton Keynes]] and the Midlands runs northwest from Marble Arch.<ref name=a-z>{{cite book|title=London A-Z|publisher=A-Z Maps / Ordnance Survey|year=2004|pp=164–165|isbn=1-84348-020-4}}</ref>
Transport within the park for people lacking mobility and disabled visitors is provided free of charge by Liberty Drives, located at Triangle Carpark.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libertydrives.org.uk/|title=Liberty Drives|accessdate=26 May 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514140949/http://libertydrives.org.uk/|archivedate=14 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
