{{Chinese name|[[Bai (surname)|Bai]]}}
'''Pai Hsiao-ye<!--with an "e"-->n''' ({{zh|first=t|s=白晓燕|t=白曉燕|p=Bái Xiăoyàn|w=Pai Hsiao-ya<!--With an "a"-->n}}; 23 June 1980 – 20 April 1997) was the only daughter of popular Taiwanese TV host and actress [[Pai Bing-bing]] and Japanese author [[Ikki Kajiwara]].

==Abduction, murder, and island-wide manhunt==

===Abduction===
Pai Hsiao-yen disappeared after leaving for her school, [[Hsing Wu High School]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://issue.udn.com/FOCUSNEWS/WHITE/a/a1-1.htm |title=白曉燕命案始末 |trans-title=Pai Bing-bing's daughter kidnapped |author1=劉峻谷 |author2=唐復年 |author3=鄭國樑 |author4=曾增勳 |date={{date|1997-04-27|dmy}} |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65S81XrKO |archivedate={{date|2012-02-14|dmy}} |deadurl=yes |newspaper=[[United Daily News]] |accessdate=September 29, 2009 |quote=十七歲的白曉燕是白冰冰的獨生女，就讀林口鄉醒吾中學二年級，十四日上午七時四十五分從林口鄉忠孝路家中出門上學，但並沒有到學校。}}</ref> on the morning of April 14, 1997. Her family received a ransom request of {{USD|5,000,000|1997|round=-4|about=yes|link=yes}} along with a severed piece of her little finger and a photograph of a bound girl.<ref name="Despair">{{cite news| author1=Healy, Tim |author2=Underwood, Laurie |url=http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/0516/feat1.html |title=A mother's despair |newspaper=[[Asiaweek]] |date=May 16, 1997 |accessdate=September 29, 2010}}</ref><!--When was the ransom note with "proof of life" discovered? Some sources say 23 Apr 1997, at which point the media may have been involved.-->

Press in Taiwan first reported the incident on April 23, 1997,<!--first evidence of this?--> which contradicted the accepted practice of reporting the kidnapping after its resolution.<ref name=Despair /> Some of the pre-planned ransom drops were aborted when kidnappers spotted police and media tailing Pai Bing-bing.<ref name=Despair /> However, after the abductors negotiated with the police for 11 days and changed the locations of payment more than 20 times, the police finally decoded the communication methods used by the abductors.<!--What reference?--> In the subsequent police raid, one suspect was arrested<!--Chen's brother in law?--> while two others escaped after an intense gun fight with the police.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}

===Murder===
Pai Hsiao-yen's mutilated body, weighted down with dumbbells, was found in a drainage ditch on April 28, 1997.<ref name=SCMP97>{{cite news |url=http://www.scmp.com/article/193976/grief-kidnap-girl-17-found-dead-ditch |title=Grief as kidnap girl, 17, found dead in ditch |author=Blatt, Jason |date={{date|1997-04-29|dmy}} |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |location=Hong Kong |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> Investigators said that she had been dead for ten days before her body's discovery. Ransom negotiations had continued after the likely time of Pai's death; an impersonator placed a telephone call to give Pai Bing-bing the impression that her daughter was alive. Tim Healy and Laurie Underwood of ''[[Asiaweek]]'' said that Pai was "apparently tortured" before her death.<ref name="Despair"/> The photograph of her naked dead body was leaked to the mass media, including the ''[[China Times]]'', which printed it.<ref name=TAHR97>{{cite web |url=http://www.tahr.org.tw/site/data/report97/eng97/e06.html |title=Taiwan Human Rights Report 1997: The Media and Human Rights |author=<!--staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Taiwan Association for Human Rights |date=1997 |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041105025449/http://www.tahr.org.tw/site/data/report97/eng97/e06.html |archivedate={{date|2004-11-05|dmy}} |deadurl=yes }}</ref>

Twelve accessories <!--note: the primary accessories were Chen's wife and her brother, who were accused of harboring a criminal; their arrest and later conviction would lead to the November 1997 Alexander hostage crisis--> were arrested, but three of the main criminals, {{Interlanguage link multi|Chen Chin-hsing (criminal)|lt=Chen Chin-hsing|zh|3=陳進興 (台灣罪犯)}} ({{zh|first=t|t=陳進興|s=|p=Chén Jìnxīng|labels=no}}), Lin Chun-sheng ({{zh|t=林春生|p=Lín Chūnshēng|labels=no}}), and Kao Tien-min ({{zh|t=高天民|p=Gāo Tiānmín|labels=no}}) escaped. A fourth person, Chang Chih-hui ({{zh|t=張志輝|p=Zhāng Zhìhuī|labels=no}}, Chen's brother-in-law) was suspected of involvement, but his sentence was eventually overturned due to insufficient evidence.<ref name=NST98>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19981226&id=BFdIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xRQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6950,4582409 |title=Kidnapper gets death for girl's murder |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1998-12-26|dmy}} |newspaper=New Straits Times |agency=Reuter |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2004/10/29/2003208806 |title=Infamous suspect Chang admits to killing woman |author=Chuang, Jimmy |date={{date|2004-10-29|dmy}} |newspaper=Taipei Times |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> An island-wide manhunt began and the police were ordered to shoot the suspects without warning if they showed any sign of resistance.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}

===Island-wide manhunt===
While being pursued, the trio abducted Taipei County councilor Tsai Ming-tang in June 1997 and a businessman surnamed Chen in August 1997.<ref name=TT99>{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/1999/10/07/0000005449 |title=Eight `bandits' are executed |author=Lin, Irene |date={{date|1999-10-07|dmy}} |newspaper=Taipei Times |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> On August 19, the trio was spotted by two foot patrol police officers on Wuchang Street (五常街) in Taipei's [[Zhongshan District, Taipei|Zhongshan District]]. A brief exchange of fire ensued and Lin turned the gun on himself after he was shot six times; one of the officers was killed and the other one was wounded. Lin died around 11:55 AM.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lin, Irene |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2000/08/31/51483 |title=Would-be hero winds up in jail |newspaper=[[Taipei Times]] |date=August 31, 2000 |accessdate=August 18, 2009 }}</ref> Reinforcement was immediately rushed to the neighborhood, and more than 800 officers conducted a thorough search, which turned up nothing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19970820&id=rJxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HBUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1170,6809196 |title=Taiwan: Wanted criminal shot dead in gunbattle |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-08-20|dmy}} |newspaper=New Straits Times |agency=Associated Press |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref>

On October 23, Kao and Chen shot and killed a plastic surgeon, his wife, and a nurse after forcing them to perform [[plastic surgery]] on them. Kao and Chen eluded a massive police search in early November 1997.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19971105&id=OIpOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GxUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5616,5764411 |title=Close call for two most wanted men |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-11-05|dmy}} |newspaper=New Straits Times |agency= |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> A few days later, Kao was spotted by the police and shot himself when police attempted to arrest him on November 17.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.taiwan-panorama.com/en/show_issue.php?id=1997128612059E.TXT |title=Aftershocks from the Pai Hsiao-yen Case |author1=Chen, Marlene |author2=Williams, Scott (translator) |date=December 1999 |newspaper=Taiwan Panorama |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref>

The last criminal, Chen Chin-hsing, broke into the residence of Colonel [[Edward McGill Alexander]], [[South African]] [[military attaché]] to Taipei, and [[Alexander family hostage crisis|took the family hostage]] on November 18,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19971119&id=e7BOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MRUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3999,5990690 |title=Taiwan's most wanted kidnapper takes five hostage, shoots two |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-11-19|dmy}} |newspaper=New Straits Times |agency=AP |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> but eventually surrendered to the police after negotiation initiated by politician [[Frank Hsieh]]. After being granted media access, Chen confessed to the April kidnapping and other crimes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19971119&id=hgUoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=os8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3359,3968835 |title=Murder suspect takes 3 South Africans hostage in Taiwan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-11-19|dmy}} |newspaper=Herald-Journal |agency=AP |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1997/Taiwan-s-Most-Wanted-Man-Gives-Up/id-639d1a81c6fd855ea70beb5fc097c56e |title=Taiwan's Most-wanted Man Gives Up |author=Huang, Annie |agency=AP |newspaper=AP News Archive |date={{date|1997-11-19|dmy}} |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05}} }}</ref> Chen was [[Capital punishment|executed]] on October 6, 1999, after being convicted in December 1998 for kidnappings, murders, and multiple counts of sexual assaults.<ref name=NST98 /><ref name=TT99 />

==Protests and resignations==
Demonstrators marched on {{date|1997-05-04|dmy}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19970505&id=rP1OAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HRUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1349,2286791 |title=15,000 in demo against crime |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-05-05|dmy}} |newspaper=New Straits Times |agency= |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} }}</ref> and {{date|1997-05-18|dmy}},<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/1997/may/19/marchers-demand-that-premier-resign/ |title=Marchers Demand That Premier Resign |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1997-05-19|dmy}} |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |agency= |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} }}</ref> demanding Premier [[Lien Chan]]'s resignation,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/1999/10/06/0000005302 |title=Chen Chin-hsing set to be executed |author=<!--staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date={{date|1999-10-06|dmy}} |newspaper=Taipei Times |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> partially over the rise in violent crime as evidenced by the then-unsolved murders of Pai, [[Peng Wan-ru]] and [[Liu Pang-yu]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/taiwan-uproar-girl-killing-article-1.763358 |title=Taiwan in uproar over girl's killing |author=Furse, Jane |agency=News Wire |date={{date|1997-05-11|dmy}} |newspaper=New York Daily News |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> Eight media organizations, including the ''China Times'', which ran the photograph of Pai's body, were condemned during the first protest.<ref name=TAHR97 />

President [[Lee Teng-hui]] offered an apology on {{date|1997-05-15|dmy}},<ref>{{cite news |url=http://taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=15261&CtNode=103 |title=President offers apology over social order issue |author=Yu, Susan |date={{date|1997-05-16|dmy}} |newspaper=Taiwan Today |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05}} }}</ref> stating Lien would be relieved of his duty as premier and the Cabinet would be reshuffled. [[Ma Ying-jeou]], who was serving as [[Minister without portfolio#Republic of China (Taiwan)|Minister without Portfolio]], resigned following the first protest.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/celebrity-killings-stir-rage-in-taiwan-1250497.html |title=Celebrity killings stir rage in Taiwan |author=Lloyd-Parry, Richard |date={{date|1997-07-13|dmy}} |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate={{date|2015-01-02|dmy}} }}</ref> [[Lin Fong-cheng]], who was serving as [[Ministry of the Interior (Taiwan)|Minister of the Interior]], also resigned his post following the first protest.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/14/world/crime-invades-a-once-peaceful-place.html |title=Crime Invades a Once-Peacful Place |author=WuDunn, Sheryl |date={{date|1997-07-14|dmy}} |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} }}</ref> Lien Chan resigned his post as [[Premier of the Republic of China|Premier]] on {{date|1997-08-22|dmy}},<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/taiwan-pm-quits-to-have-electoral-makeover-1246643.html |title=Taiwan PM quits to have electoral makeover |author=Poole, Teresa |date={{date|1997-08-22|dmy}} |newspaper=The Independent (UK) |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} }}</ref> as did the director-general of the [[National Police Agency (Republic of China)|National Police Agency]], Yao Kao-chiao.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2002/12/16/0000187376/1 |title=KMT sours to former police head |author=Huang, Sandy |date={{date|2002-12-16|dmy}} |newspaper=Taipei Times |accessdate={{date|2015-01-05|dmy}} }}</ref> Lien had repeatedly offered to resign from his other office as [[Vice President of the Republic of China|Vice President]] in the wake of the protests; eventually he retained this office until the term ended.

